Hamilton Lane closes latest fund above target at $435m























 Hamilton Lane's logo at its office. Visual from the company's website.


 





Antonia Timmerman 




                    June 15, 2017                

Alternative investment firm Hamilton Lane has closed its Strategic Opportunities Fund 2017 at $435 million, exceeding its initial target of $250 million. The announcement came just a week after it reported the closing of its $1.9 billion Secondary Fund IV LP.
The Strategic Opportunities Fund comprises a diverse set of institutions, including Taft-Hartley pension funds, insurance companies, foundations, and high-net-worth individuals. It also includes a number of existing and new investors from Asia, the Middle East, Europe, North and South America.
Structured as an annual series with a single-year investment period, the fund is designed to target private credit investments around the globe.
“The opportunity in the private credit market is meaningful and we expect it to continue to evolve and grow,” Drew Schardt, managing director and global head of the private credit team at Hamilton Lane, said in a statement.
“We believe the Strategic Opportunities series provides our clients with a flexible credit solution and unique access to these high-quality private market transactions,” he added.
A recent survey conducted by Hamilton Lane revealed that nearly two-thirds of LPs planned to increase allocations to private credit. This appetite, it said, was reflected in the strong demand for its 2017 fund.
“LPs are being thoughtful in their approach to credit, and the structure of this fund aims to deliver a high level of flexibility and optionality, while still enabling them to leverage the Hamilton Lane platform,” Emily Nomeir, principal and co-head of the product management group, explained.
Hamilton Lane has long been an active investor in targeted strategies, including credit-oriented direct investments and co-investments. While the fund represents the third dedicated vehicle of its kind, it is an extension of the company’s broader credit platform. In total, Hamilton Lane has about $20 billion in credit assets under management.
Its Secondary Fund IV LP – closed at $1.9 billion last week – is its biggest secondary fund to date. It was launched in 2016 with an initial fundraising target of $1.25 billion. The size of the secondary fund more than doubles the corpus of the preceding vehicle, Hamilton Lane Secondary Fund III, which closed at $900 million in 2013.
